WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.240
There's a question about, it looks like there's a number of ways that you can fetch data,

00:06.240 --> 00:11.520
whether using useEffect, React Query, or TanStack Query.

00:11.520 --> 00:15.360
They seem to share a lot of the same purposes.

00:15.360 --> 00:19.280
What's the use case I would use TanStack Query over, say, useEffect?

00:19.280 --> 00:23.440
That's a good question.

00:23.440 --> 00:26.400
You can choose for yourself, right?

00:26.400 --> 00:33.040
I've kind of shown you both ways because I wanted you to see.

00:33.040 --> 00:34.040
This is a personal preference.

00:34.040 --> 00:39.540
I'm going to say this is not a controversial opinion here, is that the industry tends to

00:39.540 --> 00:45.640
just use React Query when it comes to making API requests on a regular basis.

00:45.640 --> 00:49.840
This API is just a lot nicer.

00:49.840 --> 00:53.960
It has built-in caching into it.

00:53.960 --> 00:55.720
The hooks are super nice.

00:55.760 --> 00:58.360
It has refetching built into it.

00:58.360 --> 01:02.200
It has nice error handling, like all the stuff that you would have to kind of just reconstruct

01:02.200 --> 01:04.440
yourself.

01:04.440 --> 01:09.680
This is like, it's such an elegant tool, in my opinion, and honestly, one of the tools

01:09.680 --> 01:14.840
I hold up is a prime example of really good developer experiences because you can use

01:14.840 --> 01:16.360
React Query however you want.

01:16.360 --> 01:18.600
It really doesn't enforce an opinion too much on you.

01:18.600 --> 01:22.000
It's just a very useful tool that's generally applicable to almost every problem when it

01:22.040 --> 01:26.040
comes to React components making API requests.

01:26.040 --> 01:31.440
That's why I don't really feel too much controversy in saying, like, just always use this if you're

01:31.440 --> 01:34.240
using an API, right?

01:34.240 --> 01:37.560
If you want to refetch every single time, you just set the stale time to zero and all

01:37.560 --> 01:41.240
of a sudden, okay, now it's going to refetch it every single time, right?

01:41.240 --> 01:46.280
You can't remember if it's zero or infinity.

01:46.280 --> 01:52.520
I think what I did here is I think I made it always refetch or something like that.

01:52.520 --> 01:53.520
Maybe it's one.

01:53.520 --> 01:57.240
There might even be like no cache or something like that.

01:57.240 --> 02:02.120
You'd have to go look at what the actual, here it is.

02:02.120 --> 02:05.760
We'll use enabled here in just a second.

02:05.760 --> 02:10.520
You can tell it how many pages that you want it to hold max.

02:10.520 --> 02:12.400
There's a bunch of stuff.

02:12.920 --> 02:16.040
Anyway, maybe just make this one.

02:16.040 --> 02:20.040
Anyway, so when would I use use effect?

02:20.040 --> 02:21.720
Use effect still has its place.

02:21.720 --> 02:28.600
If I had to talk to local storage or something like that, I might find a library for that.

02:28.600 --> 02:32.120
I might just use an effect for that.

02:32.120 --> 02:38.720
A good example is like, okay, I loaded a component and I want to fire off analytics events.

02:38.720 --> 02:41.440
I'd use an effect for that, yeah.

02:41.480 --> 02:43.520
It still has its use cases.

02:43.520 --> 02:51.360
With remote state management, is Tantanstack a better solution or is something like ZooStan

02:51.360 --> 02:55.080
or Redux handle that better?

02:55.080 --> 02:57.640
I'm going to say that they're different tools for different jobs.

02:57.640 --> 03:03.720
You can use ZooStan or something like that with React Query.

03:03.720 --> 03:05.720
You certainly can use Redux as a cache.

03:05.720 --> 03:11.040
There's no reason that you couldn't, but they serve different purposes.

03:11.040 --> 03:17.120
The Tantanstack store is more directly competing with ZooStan and all of those.

03:17.120 --> 03:22.680
Like I said, I tend not to use any state management libraries anymore, but if I was building something

03:22.680 --> 03:37.200
like Figma, very big complicated browser app that's going to have a lot of browser-based

03:37.200 --> 03:41.560
data that's going to be shared across lots of teams, then I would use something like

03:41.560 --> 03:49.440
ZooStan to coordinate across a massive big app that has lots of app-level data.

03:49.440 --> 03:53.040
I'm not the person who's going to use it on a very small app, but on an enormous app,

03:53.040 --> 03:58.400
I think at that scale and with that many people looking at the app, it makes more sense to

03:58.400 --> 03:59.400
me.

03:59.400 --> 04:04.360
Katie Cromman uses ZooStan in our React Native courses that we just released, so if you're

04:05.200 --> 04:06.920
interested in ZooStan or you want to learn more about it.

04:06.920 --> 04:11.360
Yeah, I would say with an iOS app where you have many pages and it's all being stored

04:11.360 --> 04:13.920
in the same thing with React Native, that makes a lot of sense to me.

04:13.920 --> 04:19.280
Do you have any opinions about putting query code inside a custom hook?

04:19.280 --> 04:21.720
That's a good question.

04:21.720 --> 04:26.000
Why wouldn't I put this one in a custom hook?

04:26.000 --> 04:33.080
Because I don't think that makes it any clearer what this is doing, and I'm not going to write

04:33.480 --> 04:35.600
tests for React query.

04:35.600 --> 04:40.520
Tanner Lindley and the React or the TanStack team test it plenty more than I ever want

04:40.520 --> 04:42.480
to test it.

04:42.480 --> 04:43.840
I don't want to test my libraries.

04:43.840 --> 04:46.760
I assume my libraries test themselves.

04:46.760 --> 04:52.040
If I put this into a custom hook, there'd be nothing interesting to test about it, so

04:52.040 --> 04:53.040
I just wouldn't.

04:53.040 --> 04:59.160
However, if I had seven requests that were firing off in serial and I wanted to make

04:59.160 --> 05:02.320
sure that the right things were being called in the right order, yeah, I'd make that a

05:02.360 --> 05:03.840
custom hook.

05:03.840 --> 05:07.960
But for just one request, no, I'm okay just putting this directly in the component.

05:07.960 --> 05:13.720
I just chose these two because almost every app that you write has API requests.

05:13.720 --> 05:19.400
Almost every app you write has routing needs, or at least very frequently.

05:19.400 --> 05:24.840
So I chose these two, but there's other ones out there like virtual tables, those can be

05:24.840 --> 05:30.160
super useful, form libraries, all sorts of stuff like that.

05:30.200 --> 05:33.960
There's lots of things to talk about with CSS, and I decided to not talk too much about

05:33.960 --> 05:37.080
CSS in the intro to this.

05:37.080 --> 05:42.520
One, it's a pretty fractured ecosystem, so there's not an obvious one to teach you, like

05:42.520 --> 05:47.880
this is the answer.

05:47.880 --> 05:53.240
Once you understand React, layering in CSS is not super hard.

05:53.240 --> 05:57.520
I'll just throw in that I'm of the opinion typically, let's say if I have this pizza

05:57.520 --> 06:04.520
of the day, I'll just come in here and say pizza of the day dot CSS, and this will just

06:07.920 --> 06:14.920
be normal, not very interesting CSS, and then here in pizza of the day dot JSX, I'll just

06:15.640 --> 06:22.640
say import dot slash pizza of the day dot CSS.

06:28.520 --> 06:35.520
That's how I like to do it, it keeps it pretty simple, I'm just writing direct CSS, and actually

06:37.600 --> 06:41.680
if you really want to get into it, what I'll do is I'll actually have a directory, pizza

06:41.680 --> 06:47.240
of the day directory, I'll have the component in there, I'll have the CSS in there, I'll

06:47.240 --> 06:49.640
have all the tests for it in there.

06:49.640 --> 06:53.960
My favorite part about that pattern is, let's say we've decided later that we're going to

06:54.040 --> 07:00.760
pizza of the month, and now we need a whole new component with new tests and new CSS.

07:00.760 --> 07:05.480
If you don't do it this way, you have to go hunt for all the files and delete them individually,

07:05.480 --> 07:08.800
or even worse and even more likely is that you just don't and you leave dead code in

07:08.800 --> 07:12.560
your code base.

07:12.560 --> 07:15.640
If you structure it like that where it's just a directory of everything's kind of self-contained

07:15.640 --> 07:19.840
directory, you just delete the whole directory and you're just assured that all of the related

07:19.840 --> 07:21.040
code goes with it.

07:21.080 --> 07:25.440
I wasn't intending to talk about CSS or anything like that, but that's how I do handle it,

07:25.440 --> 07:26.560
nine times out of ten.

07:26.560 --> 07:30.840
I can hear chat now furiously just banging away, it's like, what about Tailwind?

07:30.840 --> 07:35.480
And it's like, oh, okay.

07:35.480 --> 07:40.680
I understand Tailwind, I've taught Tailwind as part of Intermediate, so if you want to

07:40.680 --> 07:47.240
see how I use Tailwind, it's Intermediate React V5, there's a section on Tailwind.

07:47.280 --> 07:50.680
I've kind of come back around to it as like, I don't really like using it.

07:50.680 --> 07:56.440
I kind of like writing CSS, but I don't judge those that do.

